ganization known as Black Nia F.O.R.C.E. Co-founded by Ras Baraka, the group was at the forefront of organizing the student mobilization at Howard during the spring of 1989 and thereafter. We Are Worth Fighting For explores how black student activists—young men and women— helped shape and resist the rightward shift and neoliberal foundations of American politics. This history adds to the literature on Black campus activism, Black Power studies, and the emerging histories of African American life in the 1980s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAfrican American college studentsxPolitical activityzWashington (D.C.)xHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican American student movementszWashington (D.C.)xHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican American universities and collegeszWashington (D.C.)xHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAdministration Building.  aAmerican national politics.  aBlack Nia F.O.R.C.E.  aBlack Power.  aBlack campus activism.  aBlack nationalist ethos.  aBlack political struggle.  aBlack radicalism.  aBlack youth movements.  aCharter Day Convocation.  aJames Cheek.  aJesse Jackson.  aLee Atwater.  aRas Baraka.  aanti-apartheid movement.  acampus politics.  acultural programs.  adirect action.  ahip hop.  ahistorically Black colleges and universities.  anationalist philosophy.  aon-campus struggles.  aphilosophy of struggle.  apresidential campaigns.  astudent activism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PA